re the costs and implications of such an approach? This book explores these questions through engaging historical case studies and traces the impact of state sovereign immunity on both plaintiffs and states. Demonstrating that the doctrine's primary effect is felt most keenly by the weakest and most politically unpopular individuals, Christopher Shortell's findings challenge arguments from both proponents and opponents of state sovereign immunity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFederal governmentzUnited States. 0aGovernment liabilityzUnited StatesxStates. 0aStates' rights (American politics). 4aPolitics and Law : American Government. 4aPolitics and Law : Constitutional Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / National.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147802840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791478028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791478028/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles